I've toured stores all over the southeast. I guarantee you I can make a better pizza than most Domino's, with the same product material from the same commissary. Quality levels per store can be pitiful. Poor dough management, quality control... all matter and it really does boil down to the operator on site.

I'm on my phone, I can't get into nitty gritty details, but I hope I kind of explained some of it!
Lol. Yeah... Just reading the other repliesü§£ yeah I got a rolex. It was over twenty years and a divorce ago, I no longer have itüò§

Yeah, but as a manager you will run that store 100 hours a week.... And be bored as shit. In our day, 20k a week for the average store was high, 20k per unit sales a week was the rolex level. Average unit weekly sales for a Domino's at the time was about 10k... Needless to say our record for 43k in one week was insane. Those were wild times. 50 drivers on a Friday night. 

Today, 8k *can* be profitable, but you would quickly want to get that to 20k... 

It can be done! We turned stores around many times... And built a few. 

We were a franchise btw.

Make a solid product every time, hiring enough people to get the product out to the customer on time and hot, and keep the customer happy... No matter what. 

Accept all competitor coupons... And specials... Deprive the competition of business...

Mail out marketing every year...

I could go on...  BUT All of these things are HARD TO DO!üòé

In 1997, our store in St. Augustine FL. Was the no 1 Domino's in the country. For three years. 

Times have changed though... I actually won my rolex watch for 20k salesü§£
